<Link id="l00636" /><CodeLine lineNumber="636"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00637" /><CodeLine lineNumber="637"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// The DepGroups array describes the dependencies of symbols being emitted on</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Attempt to claim responsibility for new definitions. This method can be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00655" /><CodeLine lineNumber="655"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// used to claim responsibility for symbols that are added to a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00656" /><CodeLine lineNumber="656"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// materialization unit during the compilation process (e.g. literal pool</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00661" /><CodeLine lineNumber="661"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00876" /><CodeLine lineNumber="876"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Represents a JIT&#39;d dynamic library.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00877" /><CodeLine lineNumber="877"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00878" /><CodeLine lineNumber="878"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This class aims to mimic the behavior of a regular dylib or shared object,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="879"><Highlight kind="comment">/// but without requiring the contained program representations to be compiled</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00880" /><CodeLine lineNumber="880"><Highlight kind="comment">/// up-front. The JITDylib&#39;s content is defined by adding MaterializationUnits,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00881" /><CodeLine lineNumber="881"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and contained MaterializationUnits will typically rely on the JITDylib&#39;s</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00882" /><CodeLine lineNumber="882"><Highlight kind="comment">/// links-against order to resolve external references (similar to a regular</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00883" /><CodeLine lineNumber="883"><Highlight kind="comment">/// dylib).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00884" /><CodeLine lineNumber="884"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00885" /><CodeLine lineNumber="885"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The JITDylib object is a thin wrapper that references state held by the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00886" /><CodeLine lineNumber="886"><Highlight kind="comment">/// ExecutionSession. JITDylibs can be removed, clearing this underlying state</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00887" /><CodeLine lineNumber="887"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and leaving the JITDylib object in a defunct state. In this state the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00888" /><CodeLine lineNumber="888"><Highlight kind="comment">/// JITDylib&#39;s name is guaranteed to remain accessible. If the ExecutionSession</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00889" /><CodeLine lineNumber="889"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is still alive then other operations are callable but will return an Error</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00890" /><CodeLine lineNumber="890"><Highlight kind="comment">/// or null result (depending on the API). It is illegal to call any operation</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00891" /><CodeLine lineNumber="891"><Highlight kind="comment">/// other than getName on a JITDylib after the ExecutionSession has been torn</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00892" /><CodeLine lineNumber="892"><Highlight kind="comment">/// down.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00893" /><CodeLine lineNumber="893"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00894" /><CodeLine lineNumber="894"><Highlight kind="comment">/// JITDylibs cannot be moved or copied. Their address is stable, and useful as</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00895" /><CodeLine lineNumber="895"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a key in some JIT data structures.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00896" /><CodeLine lineNumber="896" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/orc/jitdylib"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/orc/jitdylib/#ae9b82bdb8efb96cf82c7f3c31168c5e1">JITDylib</a> : </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/threadsaferefcountedbase/#a66adfdfd789c9f71dbf3a4c0942ef4fe">ThreadSafeRefCountedBase</a>&lt;JITDylib&gt;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00897" /><CodeLine lineNumber="897"><Highlight kind="normal">                 </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/jitlink/jitlinkdylib">jitlink::JITLinkDylib</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01448" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1448"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01449" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1449"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This method clears all resources held for the JITDylibs, puts them in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01450" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1450"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// closed state, and clears all references to them that are held by the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01451" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1451"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// ExecutionSession or other JITDylibs. No further code can be added to the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01452" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1452"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// removed JITDylibs, and the JITDylib objects will be freed once any</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01453" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1453"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// remaining JITDylibSPs pointing to them are destroyed.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01454" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1454"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01455" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1455"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This method does &#42;not&#42; run static destructors for code contained in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01456" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1456"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// JITDylibs, and each JITDylib can only be removed once.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01457" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1457"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01458" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1458"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// JITDylibs will be removed in the order given. Teardown is usually</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01459" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1459"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// independent for each JITDylib, but not always. In particular, where the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01460" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1460"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// ORC runtime is used it is expected that teardown off all JITDylibs will</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01461" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1461"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// depend on it, so the JITDylib containing the ORC runtime must be removed</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01462" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1462"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// last. If the client has introduced any other dependencies they should be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01463" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1463"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// accounted for in the removal order too.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
